\begin{abstract}
We present \textbf{µH-iOS}, a formally verified micro-hypervisor nucleus designed
to operate within the architectural and policy constraints of Apple’s iOS
platform. Unlike conventional hypervisors executing beneath a host operating
system, µH-iOS is implemented as a minimal, verifiable isolation core running in
user space and backed by Apple’s Hypervisor.framework (HVF). By aggressively
minimizing the Trusted Computing Base (TCB) and formally proving key safety
properties—memory non-interference, capability soundness, deterministic virtual
machine (VM) exit handling, and totality—µH-iOS introduces mathematically grounded
isolation guarantees to consumer mobile hardware. This work demonstrates that
meaningful formal assurance is achievable on closed platforms without kernel
modification or jailbreaks, enabling verified compute enclaves on stock iOS
devices.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
Mobile devices increasingly host sensitive workloads, including cryptographic
operations, confidential data processing, and on-device machine learning.
Virtualization is commonly used to isolate such workloads, yet most mobile
virtualization systems rely on informal reasoning and large, complex codebases.
Formal verification offers a path toward stronger guarantees but has rarely been
applied to closed consumer platforms such as iOS.

This paper introduces µH-iOS, a micro-hypervisor nucleus that applies formal
methods within Apple’s supported virtualization model. Rather than attempting to
replace the operating system, µH-iOS treats iOS and its kernel (XNU) as assumed
substrates and places a small, verifiable isolation core above the kernel using
Hypervisor.framework.

\section{Threat Model and Assumptions}

\subsection{Threat Model}
We consider adversaries capable of executing arbitrary code within guest virtual
machines, including attempts to:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item Access or modify memory belonging to other guests.
  \item Escalate privileges beyond those explicitly granted.
  \item Trigger undefined or unhandled VM exit behavior.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Out-of-Scope Threats}
We explicitly exclude hardware faults, physical attacks, side-channel attacks,
and compromise of Apple’s Secure Boot Chain or Secure Enclave.

\subsection{Assumptions}
The following components are treated as axioms:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item Apple Secure Boot enforces code integrity.
  \item XNU enforces user/kernel separation correctly.
  \item Hypervisor.framework faithfully exposes ARM EL2 virtualization.
\end{itemize}

\section{System Architecture}

\subsection{Layered Design}
µH-iOS is positioned within the following stack:
\begin{verbatim}
Guest Workloads (Linux / Unikernels / Sandboxes)
----------------------------------------------
µH-iOS Core (Formally Verified Micro-Hypervisor)
----------------------------------------------
Apple Hypervisor.framework (HVF)
----------------------------------------------
XNU Kernel (Assumed, Unverified)
----------------------------------------------
Apple Secure Boot Chain + Hardware
\end{verbatim}

Policy enforcement resides exclusively within µH-iOS, while lower layers provide
only mechanism.

\section{Design Goals}
The system is guided by four goals:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
  \item Minimize the Trusted Computing Base.
  \item Prove strong isolation and safety properties.
  \item Eliminate undefined behavior in VM exit handling.
  \item Remain compatible with stock iOS devices.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Formal System Model}

\subsection{Global State}
\begin{definition}[System State]
The global system state $\Sigma$ is defined as:
\[
\Sigma = \{ VMs, Memory, Caps, Scheduler, Exits \}
\]
where all mutable state is explicitly represented.
\end{definition}

\subsection{VM State Machine}
\[
VMState ::= Created \mid Runnable(CPUState) \mid Trapped(ExitReason, CPUState) \mid Halted
\]

\section{Formal Invariants}

\begin{theorem}[Memory Non-Interference]
For any two distinct virtual machines $vm_1 \neq vm_2$,
\[
memory(vm_1) \cap memory(vm_2) = \emptyset.
\]
\end{theorem}

\begin{theorem}[Capability Soundness]
An operation may occur if and only if the executing VM possesses the
corresponding capability prior to execution.
\end{theorem}

\begin{theorem}[Deterministic Exit Handling]
Given identical VM state and exit reason, the resulting state transition is
deterministic.
\end{theorem}

\begin{theorem}[Totality]
All VM exits are handled by a defined transition; no undefined behavior exists.
\end{theorem}

\section{Implementation}

\subsection{Language Choices}
The µH-iOS core is implemented in Rust to align with the formal model and reduce
memory safety risks. Swift is used for iOS application orchestration, with minimal
C bindings for Hypervisor.framework.

\subsection{Core Structure}
The verified core includes modules for VM lifecycle management, memory mapping,
capability enforcement, and exit dispatching. Unsafe code is excluded from core
logic.

\section{Hypervisor.framework Integration}
Hypervisor.framework is used solely as an execution mechanism. µH-iOS enforces:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item One HVF context per VM.
  \item No shared guest memory regions.
  \item Centralized, deterministic exit handling.
\end{itemize}

\section{iOS Application Integration}
µH-iOS is packaged as a signed iOS application using supported entitlements. This
ensures deployability on stock devices without kernel modification.

\section{Extensions and Composition}
µH-iOS serves as a root of trust for higher-level orchestration systems, including
workload schedulers and verified compute pipelines.

\section{Evaluation}
Evaluation focuses on TCB size, proof completeness, isolation correctness, and
platform compatibility rather than raw performance.

\section{Related Work}
This work draws inspiration from verified microkernels such as seL4 while
differing fundamentally in deployment environment and trust assumptions.

\section{Limitations and Future Work}
Limitations include reliance on assumed correctness of XNU and HVF, and the
exclusion of side-channel defenses. Future work includes richer device models and
expanded formal coverage.

\section{Conclusion}
µH-iOS demonstrates that formal verification and strong isolation guarantees are
achievable on closed mobile platforms. By introducing a small, verifiable nucleus
above the operating system, µH-iOS enables verified computation on iOS without
violating platform security policies.

